rComments: Dilevko is clearly brilliant, but pursues his own agenda. He's interested in going back to the roots of the discipline, and teaches with that in mind, never mind the reality of the field for graduating students. His assignments are punishing, with byzantine instructions and dozens of criteria. He's personable, but that's the best I can say for him.

He barely lectures and makes you do group assignments, he is clear about what he wants in the syllabus for assignments but will negate what he wants in class and tell you not to do what he said to do. The only good thing about the class is that there is no class reading involved- only for assignments.
Dr. Dilevko is simply amazing!
He's all over the place and asks for way too much. Other sections of the class with different profs were much simpler. Not recommended
Incredibly intelligent and organized educator. There are no surprises - he outlines exactly what he will teach you and exactly what he wants from you. Incredibly approachable!
He's very, very intense, and very, very good. Best course I took, though I was sometimes met with looks of bewilderment when I said that to other students.

This professor is brilliant.  He's critical, and he ties everything up so nicely, you will definitely learn! Excellent value for the $, prob the best course I've taken so far in my 1.5/2 year MA program.  Do not be daunted by the coursework...even if you can get by with decent grade, take the course, cause the knowledge imparted is brilliant!

Likely the best professor of librarianship in North America.  His classes require a lot of work, but it is because librarianship requires a lot of work.    This is especially true for academic librarians.  He places very high standards, but if you do the work properly, he will write you the letter needed to get the job.  And you will learn!
This course required way too much writing and group work.  A 20+ page paper is not uncommon and it can easily suck up all of your time.  Informative, and valuable, but more work than it was worth

The workload in a Dilevko course is typically higher than the average class, but well worth the extra effort.  In a faculty that's rapidly becoming a student factory, this prof actually puts his students first.  Goes beyond the boilerplate rhetoric and is extemely accomodating.

He is an excellent teacher and extremely understanding. When I had to miss a lot of classes for personal reasons, he went out of his way to accomodate me to the extent that he could. He is one of the few reasons I have any good comments to make about this program!
Dilevko is wierd, but in a good way. He's ridiculously smart and if you approach him for help, he is both warm and useful. A good soul for a crappy, hard-to-teach course.
He rocks!!!
Very useful classes for future librarians.
He taught stats and, even with a background in stats, he still confused me. He just pursues his own agenda during lectures and wins over students with humour, but really has nothing to say.
Dilevko is very boring and pedantic
I took a bunch of classes with him during my time at FIS and found them to be the most useful and interesting during my time there.

Courageous lecturer, but occassionally wandered into "coo-coo-banannas" territory. Class sucked more because of its structure and reading materials than him.  He did the best he could with a lame course that noone else on staff wanted to teach. Every department needs a Dilevko on staff though :)
Impressive
Lively instructor; 'interesting' sense of humour and assignments were time-consuming but challenging; one of the better profs at FIS; highly recommend his Reader's Advisory course
This man is crazy, in a way that becomes less and less interesting as the semester progresses.
